courses.name: Biomedical Research at the Cutting Edge

cmCourseInfo.description: Explore the thought processes, logic, motivation, techniques, analysis and impact of recent high-profile publications to gain insight into the enterprise of science. Outstanding scientists present recent high-impact papers, and students will examine the research in depth, focusing on the underlying questions, experimental approach, results and significance. Restricted to first-year students. Not eligible for CR/NCR option.
cmCourseInfo.title: Biomedical Research at the Cutting Edge
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: SBI4U and SCH4U (Grade 12 University Preparation Biology and Chemistry); permission of Department

notes.content:
Timetable Instructions

Term test will take place Tuesdays in person from 18:00 to 19:00 Toronto time (3 Tuesdays over the course).

Delivery Instructions

Lectures will be delivered online. Students will be expected to watch asynchronous lecture videos prior to class meetings; learning is self-paced and not reliant on a meeting schedule. Term tests will be timed and will take place in person Tuesdays from 18:00 to 19:00 (Toronto time) on scheduled dates (TBA). Lectures 2h/week and optional synchronous help sessions 1h/week (these will be recorded). 

The final in-person assessment will be announced by the Faculty of Registrar’s office.

courses.name: Introduction to Physiologic Adaptations of Marine Mammals

cmCourseInfo.description: Systems approach to physiology of marine mammals in their aquatic environment. Highlights unique features of cardiovascular, respiratory, renal, urinary, and reproductive systems. Introduces relevant physiology, and makes comparisons to human condition and disease.
cmCourseInfo.title: Introduction to Physiologic Adaptations of Marine Mammals
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: (BIO120H1, BIO130H1), CHM136H1/CHM151Y1. Students who do not have all of the required prerequisites are encouraged to contact the course coordinator to seek a waiver.

courses.name: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I

cmCourseInfo.description: Control systems, feedback, networks, and both neonatal and adult cardiovascular and respiratory control are the topics examined in detail using homeostasis as a unifying theme. Tutorials involve computer simulations, case studies and/or experimental design. This course is designed for students in the Physiology Specialist and Biological Physics Specialist Programs, although permission is granted to students in other programs upon approval by the Department.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology I
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BCH210H1, PSL300H1, PSL301H1, MAT100-series

courses.name: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II

cmCourseInfo.description: Focus on two topics: the brain and pregnancy. Delve into the physiology of the central nervous system along with associated diseases as model systems. Learn about fetal and maternal adaptations during pregnancy and the consequences of maladaptation. The course is designed for Physiology Specialist students, although permission is granted to other students upon Departmental approval.
cmCourseInfo.title: Topics in Cellular, Molecular and Organismic Physiology II
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BCH210H1, PSL300H1, PSL301H1, MAT100-series

cmCourseInfo.description: Regenerative medicine promises to restore body function that has been lost due to disease, damage or age. Students will explore selected molecular, stem cell and tissue engineering developments to better understand how the body normally functions and how cells, tissues, and organs can be repaired or replaced.
cmCourseInfo.title: Regenerative Medicine
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: PSL300H1, PSL301H1

cmCourseInfo.description: This course provides an in-depth review of the development and function of the male and female reproductive systems. Topics include sex determination and differentiation, steroidogenesis, gametogenesis, hormonal control of the reproductive axis, the female ovulatory cycle, fertilization and implantation, infertility and assisted reproduction approaches. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL420H1/LMP2100H
cmCourseInfo.title: Reproduction: Development and Function
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: A minimum grade of 78% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

courses.name: Pregnancy and Birth: From Implantation to Newborn Life

cmCourseInfo.description: General overview of the integrated physiological events associated with fetal development, pregnancy and birth. The approach emphasizes physiological processes using insights gained from studies of humans, animals, cells and genes. Where appropriate the clinical consequences of aberrant development are reviewed. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL421H1/PSL1421H
cmCourseInfo.title: Pregnancy and Birth: From Implantation to Newborn Life
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: A final grade of 75% or higher in each of PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum is not reached, please contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

courses.name: Cellular and Molecular Basis of Endocrine Disorders

cmCourseInfo.description: Explore how researchers uncover the molecular and cellular basis of endocrine disorders. Learn about experimental design, state-of-the-art research tools, and data interpretation. Topics include disorders in: hormone regulation, secretion and action; circadian rhythms; and sexual development and reproduction. Each week students engage in class discussion related to research seminars delivered by faculty.
cmCourseInfo.title: Cellular and Molecular Basis of Endocrine Disorders
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: PSL300H1, PSL301H1, PSL350H1/BCH311H1/CSB349H1/MGY311Y1

cmCourseInfo.title: Integrative Metabolism and its Endocrine Regulation

A review of basic neuroanatomy and physiology followed by in-depth study of selected sensory and motor systems, with an emphasis on clinical applications in the second term. courses.name: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion

cmCourseInfo.description: Exocytosis and other aspects of secretion mainly in neurons and neuroendocrine cells, but also in pancreatic cells. Topics include synapse anatomy and physiology, synaptic plasma membrane and vesicle proteins, membrane fusion, genetic tools, endocrine secretion, plasticity in neurotransmitter release, diseases arising from secretion defects.
cmCourseInfo.title: Mechanisms of Neural and Endocrinal Secretion
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: BCH210H1, PSL300H1/(BIO240H1, BIO241H1), PSL350H1/CSB349H1/BCH311H1/MGY311Y1

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

cmCourseInfo.description: Biophysics and molecular biology of ion channels. Topics include equivalent circuits for cells, molecular structure of voltage-gated channels, distribution of channels, relationship between single-channel and whole-cell recording, and regulation of channel function by voltage, phosphorylation, G-proteins and metabolites. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL452H1/PSL1452H
cmCourseInfo.title: Membrane Physiology
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText:
PSL300H1, PSL301H1

A minimum grade of 75% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

breadthTypes.description: BR=4 Living Things and Their Environment

cmCourseInfo.description: Heart anatomy and development, ion channels and contractile proteins involved in cardiac and smooth muscle contraction are studied. Emphasis is on regulation of electrical and contractile function of kinases, metabolism, volume and ions. Joint undergraduate/graduate course - PSL462H1/PSL1462H
cmCourseInfo.title: Molecular Aspects of Cardiovascular Function
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText:
PSL300H1, PSL301H1

cmCourseInfo.description: Development of the cardiovascular system from conception to adulthood with particular emphasis on maturational changes, age-related differences and developmental problems from cellular/molecular to whole organ/system.
cmCourseInfo.title: Cardiovascular Physiology
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: PSL300H1, PSL301H1

cmCourseInfo.description: This course covers the physiology underlying sleep and circadian rhythms, and their impact on important physiological processes and health. The integrative nature of the basic physiological processes is emphasized via discussions and clinical presentations. Overall, the aim is to present the full spectrum of integrative physiology from molecules and cells to understanding the sick patient.
cmCourseInfo.title: Sleep Physiology and Chronobiology
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText:
PSL300H1, PSL301H1

A minimum grade of 75% is required in PSL300H1 and PSL301H1. If minimum grade has not been met students are advised to contact the Department of Physiology at physiology.undergrad@utoronto.ca for approval.

cmCourseInfo.title: Diving Physiology of Marine Mammals
cmCourseInfo.prerequisitesText: (BIO270H1, BIO271H1)/PSL201Y1/PSL300H1, PSL301H1; PSL280H1
